imshaw used their work to advance their own private and public political concerns through astute manoeuvrings both in the expanding publishing industry and against the partisan expectations of an ever-growing readership. The chapters investigate their dialogue with a contemporary politics that included the topics of education, cosmopolitanism, language, empire, economics, philanthropy, socialism, the marriage 'market', the publishing industry, readership(s), the commercial market and employment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexIrish authorsxHistory and criticismxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aEnglish literaturexIrish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aFeminism and literature.  aIrish women’s writing.  aLiterature and history.  aNineteenth-century Irish literature.  aPolitics and literature.  aPublishing history.  aTwentieth-century Irish literature.  aWomen and public engagement.1 aAnnat, Aurelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArrington, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoak, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansson, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelleher, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahony, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaume, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, James H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Neill, Ciaran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular